---

<ResourcePage
  title="Depression & Bipolar Disorder"
  description="Educational resources about mood disorders, treatment approaches, medications, therapy, and long-term wellness."
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>
<article class="resource-main-content reveal">

            <h2>Understanding Mood Disorders</h2>

            <p>
              Depression and bipolar disorder are mood disorders that can affect emotional wellbeing, energy levels,
              sleep, motivation, concentration, and relationships. These conditions are common and treatable, but
              symptoms can vary significantly from person to person.
            </p>

            <p>
              Major depression may involve persistent sadness, hopelessness, low motivation, or loss of interest in
              previously enjoyable activities. Bipolar disorder can involve episodes of depression as well as periods of
              elevated mood, increased energy, impulsivity, or decreased need for sleep.
            </p>

            <h2>Common Symptoms</h2>

            <ul class="resource-list">
              <li>Persistent sadness or emotional numbness</li>
              <li>Loss of motivation or interest</li>
              <li>Changes in sleep or appetite</li>
              <li>Fatigue or low energy</li>
              <li>Difficulty concentrating</li>
              <li>Periods of elevated mood or impulsivity</li>
              <li>Thoughts of hopelessness or self-harm</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Treatment Options</h2>

            <p>
              Mood disorders are highly treatable with appropriate care. Treatment may include psychiatric evaluation,
              medication management, psychotherapy, lifestyle interventions, sleep stabilization, and stress management
              techniques.
            </p>

            <p>
              Consistent support, structured routines, and early intervention can improve long-term emotional stability
              and quality of life. Individuals experiencing severe mood symptoms should seek professional support
              promptly.
            </p>

            <h2>Crisis and Emergency Support</h2>

            <p>
              If you or someone you know is experiencing suicidal thoughts or an emotional crisis, immediate support is
              available through the 988 Suicide & Crisis Lifeline or local emergency services. Seeking help is an
              important step toward recovery and safety.
            </p>

          </article>

          <aside class="resource-sidebar reveal">

            <div class="resource-sidebar-card">

              <h3>
                Trusted Organizations
              </h3>

              <ul>
                <li><a href="https://www.nimh.nih.gov/health/topics/depression" target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer">NIMH Depression</a></li>
                <li><a href="https://www.dbsalliance.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Depression and
                    Bipolar Support Alliance</a></li>
                <li><a href="https://988lifeline.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">988 Suicide & Crisis
                    Lifeline</a></li>
              </ul>

            </div>

            <div class="resource-sidebar-card">

              <h3>
                Local & Crisis Support
              </h3>

              <p>
                For urgent emotional support, call or text 988 for the Suicide & Crisis Lifeline. Residents in Addison,
                Bloomingdale, DuPage County, and the greater Chicagoland area may also benefit from local counseling
                centers, hospitals, and emergency mental health services.
              </p>

            </div>

            <div class="resource-sidebar-card">

              <h3>
                When To Seek Help
              </h3>

              <p>
                Consider professional evaluation if symptoms are affecting work, school, sleep, relationships, emotional
                wellbeing, or daily functioning. Early support and treatment can improve long-term outcomes and quality
                of life.
              </p>

            </div>

          </aside>


</ResourcePage>
